<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900501-0003</DOCNO><DOCID>900501-0003.</DOCID><HL>   UPS Could be Fined   As Much as $625,000   On OSHA Charges</HL><DATE>05/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- United Parcel Service faces possible federalfines of $625,000 on charges of worker-safety violationsafter a call from Nassau County, N.Y., police warned OSHAthat a UPS driver was injured by a hazardous chemical carriedby his delivery truck.   The Labor Department's Occupational Safety and HealthAdministration charged UPS with 312 willful record-keepingviolations at its Uniondale, N.Y., facility, including 310instances of improper recording of employees on restrictedwork activity. OSHA said it has issued numerous citations forrecord-keeping violations by UPS over the past 16 years.</LP><TEXT>   United Parcel Service of America Inc., the closely heldpackage-delivery company based in Greenwich, Conn., said itwas studying the complaint and hadn't decided on a response.Most of the citation, however, dealt with &quot;alleged violationsof written procedures and guidelines,&quot; which are &quot;complex andsubject to conflicting interpretations,&quot; UPS said.   The company also was cited for failure to develop anemergency response plan, or to train all workers in how torespond to an emergency involving hazardous materials, andfor not supplying a proper respirator for employees handlinghazardous-materials spills.   OSHA said its inspection of the Uniondale facilityresulted from a call from the Nassau County policehazardous-materials team, after methylene chloride, asuspected carcinogen, spilled from a box bound for deliveryin the truck. The driver touched the chemical, then put hishand to his face, sustaining hand and facial injuries, OSHAsaid.   UPS has 15 working days to contest the citations beforethe independent Occupational Safety and Health ReviewCommission.</TEXT></DOC>